_DST             = AKDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -8\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 77\n|elevation_ft             = 253\n|coordinates              = {{coord|60|12|30|N|154|18|24|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 99653\n|area_code                = [[Area code 907|907]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 02-62620\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1408208\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Port Alsworth''' is a [[census-designated place]] (CDP) in [[Lake and Peninsula Borough, Alaska|Lake and Peninsula Borough]], [[Alaska]], United States. It is {{convert|165|mi}} by air southwest of [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]. The population was 159 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]],<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US0262620| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001), Port Alsworth CDP, Alaska| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=August 15, 2019| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213070833/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US0262620| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> up from 104 in 2000.\n\nPort Alsworth was founded in 1950 by Babe Alsworth, a [[missionary]] and [[bush pilot]], and Mary Alsworth, who was the town's first [[postmaster]].\n\nPort Alsworth is located on private land within [[Lake Clark National Park and Preserve]] and the site of the national park's field headquarters.\n\n[[Samaritan's Purse]] operates a lodge for wounded United States military veterans located within the town for \"Operation Heal Our Patriots\" (OHOP). There is also a summer camp called \"Tanalian Bible Camp\" where youth, ages 8\u201319, from the surrounding villages can attend.\n\nFrom the summer of 2013 to the spring of 2014, the local Tanalian School underwent renovation and a dearly needed expansion. The renovation involved tripling school square footage, all new furniture, and doubling the size of the gym.\n\n==Geography==\nPort Alsworth is located in northern Lake and Peninsula Borough at {{coord|60|12|30|N|154|18|24|W|type:city}} (60.208281, -154.306586).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> It sits on the south shore of [[Lake Clark (Alaska)|Lake Clark]] at the mouth of the Tanalian River.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the CDP has a total area of {{convert|58.8|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|58.65|km2|order=flip}} are land and {{convert|0.16|km2|order=flip|2}}, or 0.27%, are water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Climate==\nPort Alsworth has a [[continental subarctic climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] Dfc).\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Port Alsworth\n|single line = Y\n| Jan record high F = 54\n| Feb record high F = 54\n| Mar record high F = 56\n| Apr record high F = 70\n| May record high F = 85\n| Jun record high F = 89\n| Jul record high F = 89\n| Aug record high F = 87\n| Sep record high F = 75\n| Oct record high F = 66\n| Nov record high F = 56\n| Dec record high F = 53\n| year record high F = 89\n| Jan high F = 22.8\n| Feb high F = 27\n| Mar high F = 33.3\n| Apr high F = 43.7\n| May high F = 55.6\n| Jun high F = 64.1\n| Jul high F = 67.4\n| Aug high F = 65\n| Sep high F = 56.1\n| Oct high F = 41.7\n| Nov high F = 30.7\n| Dec high F = 24.5\n| year high F = 44.3\n| Jan low F = 5.4\n| Feb low F = 7.6\n| Mar low F = 11.3\n| Apr low F = 24.4\n| May low F = 34.1\n| Jun low F = 42.3\n| Jul low F = 46.8\n| Aug low 