nnial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Trefon Dena'ina Fish Cache - Port Alsworth Alaska.jpg|thumb|The historic Trefon Dena'ina Fish Cache in Port Alsworth]]\n[[File:Wilder Natwick LLC airport.jpg|thumb|Wilder/Natwick LLC airport]]\nPort Alsworth first appeared on the 1940 U.S. Census as the unincorporated village of \"Tanalian Point\". It next appeared on the 1960 census under its present name of Port Alsworth. It did not reappear again until 1990, when it was made a census-designated place (CDP).\n\nAs of the census<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> of 2000, there were 104 people, 34 households, and 24 families residing in the CDP. The population density was 4.6 people per square mile (1.8/km\u00b2). There were 70 housing units at an average density of 3.1/sq&nbsp;mi (1.2/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the CDP was 77.88% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 4.81% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], and 17.31% from two or more races.\n\nThere were 34 households out of which 47.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 67.6% were married couples living together, 2.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 26.5% were non-families. 23.5% of all households were made up of individuals and none had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 3.06 and the average family size was 3.64.\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 41.3% under the age of 18, 7.7% from 18 to 24, 28.8% from 25 to 44, 18.3% from 45 to 64, and 3.8% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 26 years. For every 100 females, there were 85.7 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 84.8 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $58,750.00, and the median income for a family was $62,083. Males had a median income of $50,417 versus $17,083 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $21,716. There were no families and 6.0% of the population living below the [[poverty line]], including no under eighteens and none of those over 64.\n\n==Transportation==\n[[Air taxi]]s serve the private [[Port Alsworth Airport]] and the public Wilder/Natwick LLC Airport.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.thefarmlodge.com/index.html The Farm Lodge]\n* [https://www.adn.com/bush-pilot/article/legends-alaska-aviation-glen-alsworth/2012/09/29/ Glen Alsworth]\n* [http://lakeandpen.hosted.civiclive.com/residents/about_l_p_b/villages/port_alsworth Village of Port Alsworth]\n* [http://library.state.ak.us/asp/edocs/2007/04/ocm71155611.pdf  Subsistence harvests and uses of wild resources in Iliamna, Newhalen, Nondalton, Pedro Bay, and Port Alsworth, Alaska, 2004 / by James A. Fall ... [et al.&#93;.] Hosted by [https://web.archive.org/web/20071012120420/http://library.state.ak.us/asp/ Alaska State Publications Program]\n\n{{Lake and Peninsula Borough, Alaska}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Lake and Peninsula Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Alaska]]\n", "name_user": "Writhing", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Port_Alsworth,_Alaska"}
{"title_page": "Rage 2", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Rage 2\n| image = Rage 2 cover art.jpg\n| developer = [[Avalanche Studios]]{{efn|Additional development by [[id Software]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/08/11/rage-2-is-primarily-being-developed-by-avalanche-studios-id-working-with-them-on-a-creative-level|title=Rage 2 Is Primarily Being Developed by Avalanche Studios, Id Working with Them on a Creative Level|first=Tom|last=Marks|work=[[IGN]]|date=August 10, 2018|accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref>}}\n| publisher = [[Bethesda Softworks]]\n| director = Magnus Nedfors \n| producer = {{Unbulleted list|Erik Olsen|Anders Strid}}\n| writer = {{Unbulleted list|Odd Ahlgren|Loke Wallmo}}\n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = \n| engine =\n| composer = {{Unbulleted list|Johan Nilsson|Andreas Kinger|Eirik R\u00f8land{{efn|Additional music by Jukka Rintam\u00e4ki.<ref>{{cite video game |title=Rage 2 |developer=[[Avalanche Studios]] |publisher=[[Bethesda Softworks]] |date=2019-05-14 |platform=Windows |version= |scene=Ending credits |level= |language= |quote= }}</ref>}}}}\n| series = \n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Google Stadia|Stadia]]}}\n| released = May 14, 2019\n| genre = [[First-person shooter]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Rage 2''''' is a [[first-person shooter]] [[video game]] developed by [[Avalanche Studios]] in conjunction with [[id Software]] and published by [[Bethesda Softworks]]. The game is the sequel to the 2011 game ''[[Rage (video game)|Rage]]''. The game was released for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] on May 14, 2019. It received mixed reviews from critics, with praise for its combat but criticism for its story, characters, and open world gameplay.\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Rage 2'' is a [[first-person shooter]]. Players assume control of a ranger named Walker, who is free to explore the game's [[apocalyptic fiction|apocalyptic]] [[open world]].  Players are given control over some of Walker's attributes, such as their gender, skills, or attire. Walker is able to wield various firearms and tools to fight against enemies, including returning weapons such as the wingstick. Players can develop Walker's skills with Nanotrite-based powers. Through a mode called Overdrive, Walker's guns do more damage, enemies drop more energy and they get healed constantly \u2014 providing players with an aggressive way to mow down enemies.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://gamegator.net/news/article/rage-2-post-post-apocalypse|title=Rage 2 - Welcome the Post-Post-Apocalypse!|website=GameGator|language=en|access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/05/15/rage-2-gameplay-reveal/|title='Rage 2' brings the frenetic action of 'Doom' to an open world|first=Jon|last=Fingas|work=[[Engadget]]|date=May 15, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> Nanotrites from the first game, which act as special powers and ability boosts, can be used to increase combat efficiency. The game features [[vehicular combat]], including trucks, buggies and gyrocopters, with the player being able to drive any vehicle in the game's world.<ref name=\"preorder\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2018-rage-2-what-we-know-and-want/1100-6459136/|title=E3 2018: Rage 2 -- What We Know And Want|first=Edmond|last=Trans|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=June 7, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nPlayers assume control of Walker, the last Ranger of Vineland, who must survive in a world inhabited by dangerous mutants and crazed bandits after it was hit by the asteroid [[99942 Apophis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rage-2-trailer-shows-off-cars-guns-special-powers-and-a-weird-post-apocalypse/|title=Rage 2 trailer shows off cars, guns, special powers, and a weird post-apocalypse|last=Chalk|first=Andy|date=June 13, 2018|work=[[PC Gamer]]|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> The majority of humankind died during this apocalyptic event. While new settlements and factions emerged, a group called the Authority declared themselves the new military power. The game's prologue begins in Walker's home, Vineland, a city founded by former Ark residents and their descendants. Vineland gets stormed by the Authority's rebuilt Abadon mutant armies, and Walker's adoptive Aunt Prowley is killed by General Cross. Prowley leaves a pre-recorded holotape asking Walker to carry out Project Dagger, a mission conceived to stop General Cross. Walker is inducted as the last Ranger, a group of Ark survivors whose nanotrite-powered suits give them enhanced combat abilities. They are asked by Prowley's recording to find the three other members of Project Dagger; Loosum Hagar, Marshall, and Dr. Kvasir. Prowley's biological daughter, Lily, provides Walker with the Phoenix, an indestructible vehicle to travel the Wasteland, and promises to rebuild Vineland in the Ranger's absence.\n\nMarshall is found in the town of Gunbarrel. Walker is asked to assist him in restoring power to Gunbarrel before Marshall and retrieving Gulo, a scout sent by Marshall from an hostile enemy clan named the Immortal Shrouded. The scout's last defiant act was to swallow the recorder with the bunker's location, which Walker recovers from her already-carved-out gut. They proceed to the bunker, wiping out both the Immortal Shrouded and the Authority patrol sent to dislodge them, and secures the data necessary to penetrate the Authority's security scans.\n\nLoosum Hagar is the mayor of Wellspring, a major travel hub in the Wasteland. When Walker arrives at her office, the Ranger is forced to fight off an assassination attempt against the mayor, who she suspects Wasteland tycoon Klegg Clayton of masterminding the attack. Klegg tries to kill Walker after admitting he was on a first name basis with General Cross. Fighting through Klegg's henchmen, Walker warns Loosum of the plot against Wellspring and uncovers a Xerxes MK III Authority Predator tank hidden in Klegg's catacombs beneath the town. The Ranger follows Klegg to an Authority bunker, to witness General Cross put down his unsuccessful lackey for failing to deliver Wellspring. Exploring deeper into the facility, Walker finds evidence that the Authority is building massive Abadon mutants piece by piece, calling them \"Titans\" and planning to unleash them on the rest of the Wasteland. Walker tears the fusion core out of a huge, half-build Titan, causing a chain reaction that destroys the facility and simultaneously securing a power source for the Xerxes III Predator tank that is necessary to complete Project Dagger.\n\nDr. Anton Kvasir is a master of genetic manipulation tasked to create a nanotrite virus that would disable General Cross' ability to clone himself indefinitely to prolong his life. The scientist invites Walker into his sanctum, where he says he is held back from finishing his project by insufficient computing power. Walker is asked to land Eco-Pod 15, the last of a series of satellites tasked with re-seeding the Earth with life in the event that the Apophis meteor rendered the planet barren after impact. After entering EDEN Space Center, Kvasir hacks the Vault mainframe to grant Walker the status of [[President of the United States|POTUS]] to ensure they can access every aspect of the EDEN Project. Successful in lowering Eco-Pod 15 back to Earth, Walker slaves its processor to Kvasir's mainframe before being forced to fight off an Authority strike force. Kvasir sends Walker on a mission to retrieve a DNA sample from General Cross. Raiding an Authority base for the sample, Walker frees captives from Vineland whose DNA was used in horrific cloning and mutant experiments. Walker decapitates General Cross after defeating him in battle, though a fresh clone of the General escapes. Back at Kvasir's lab, the doctor uses Cross' severed head to produce the nanotrite virus that was his part of Project Dagger.\n\nWith the three components, Walker initiates the final phase of Project Dagger by infiltrating the Authority HQ. Able to gain entry to the compound by impersonating General Cross, the Ranger is discovered by the real general. General Cross meets Walker while riding a gigantic Cyber Titan, and the two battle. Killing the Titan, Walker stabs Cross in the eye with the Nanotrite Virus, causing his DNA to be corrupted to prevent future clones from being created. However, unbeknownst to Walker due to Kvasir's manipulation, the Ranger's own nanotrites are also susceptible to the virus. Choking to death alongside the broken body of General Cross, Walker is saved by the intervention of Lily, who returns them to Hagar's Wellspring office for medical treatment. With Lily's gun to his head, Dr. Kvasir works frantically to save the Ranger. When he succeeds, the doctor begs for his life from the enraged Lily, who spares him. The game ends with Walker regaining consciousness and thanking Lily for her help, promising to continue helping the Wasteland as the Last Ranger.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/rage-2-rage-1-story-1202840312/|title=Bethesda Confirms 'Rage 2' Will Continue 'Rage 1's' Storyline|first=Vikki|last=Blake|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 12, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n''Rage 2'' is a joint development between [[id Software]] and [[Avalanche Studios]]. Avalanche was selected as the collaboration partner for the project as id Software was impressed by Avalanche's work on ''[[Just Cause 3]]'', especially its physics-based emergent gameplay. According to [[Tim Willits]], the team hoped that the sequel could deliver on the promise made by the first game, which was limited by technology during its time of release. Willits added that ''Rage 2'' was designed to be the player's \"power fantasy\", thus they ensured that they will not feel underpowered at the beginning of the game. The game features a colorful color palette so as to distinguish itself from other id Software's games.<ref name=\"Willits interview\"/> ''Rage 2'' utilizes Avalanche Studios' proprietary Apex [[game engine]] instead of [[id Tech]], which had been used for the predecessor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/105027/rage-2-uses-just-cause-series-engine-instead-of-idtech|title=Rage 2 Uses Just Cause Series' Engine Instead of idTech|first=Charles |last=Singletary|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> The Apex engine allowed the team to create detailed indoor environments as well as broad outdoor locations, also allowing players to transition between these worlds without any loading screens.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Willits interview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/06/12/rage-2-tim-willits/|title=We asked id Software studio director Tim Willits about their Avalanche partnership, open world fatigue and Rage 2 on Switch|first=James|last=Billcliffe|date=June 12, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018|work=[[VG 247]]}}</ref> The game engine uses the [[Vulkan (API)|Vulkan]] API exclusively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techpowerup.com/review/rage-2-benchmark-performance-test/|title=RAGE 2 Benchmark Test & Performance Analysis|author=W1zzard|date=May 13, 2019|website=TechPowerUp}}</ref>\n\nA sequel to ''[[Rage (video game)|Rage]]'' was hinted by Bethesda's Pete Hines, who believed that both ''Rage'' and ''[[The Evil Within]]'' had sold enough to warrant sequels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/08/09/bethesda-discusses-rage-and-the-evil-within-sequels|title=Bethesda Discusses Rage and The Evil Within Sequels|first=Matt|last=Porter|work=[[IGN]]|date=August 9, 2016|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> In mid-May 2018, rumors of the sequel were fueled when [[Walmart]] Canada's website updated its video game sections with several as-yet-unannounced titles, which included ''Rage 2''. Bethesda poked fun at Walmart over social media in the following days, but this turned into more direct hints of the sequel's existence.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-05-10-despite-all-their-rage-bethesda-tweet-puts-walmart-in-a-cage | title = Despite all their Rage, Bethesda tweet puts Walmart in a cage | first = Wesley | last = Yin-Poole | date = May 10, 2018 | accessdate = May 14, 2018 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> Bethesda formally revealed ''Rage 2'' on May 14, 2018 with a teaser trailer and a gameplay trailer the next day.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/5/14/17351926/rage-2-trailer-ps4-xbox-one-pc-bethesda | title = Rage 2 trailer hints at silly sequel, mixing Mad Max with Borderlands  | first = Chris | last = Plante | date = May 14, 2018 | accessdate = May 14, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref> The game was released on [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] on May 14, 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rage-2-being-developed-in-part-by-just-cause-studi/1100-6458925/ | title = Rage 2 Being Developed In Part By Just Cause Studio; Confirmed For PS4, Xbox One, PC | first = Chris | last=  Pereira | date = May 14, 2018 | accessdate = May 14, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url =  http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/05/15/rage-2-release-window-gameplay-details-announced | title = Rage 2: Release Window, Gameplay Details Announced | first=  Joe | last = Skrebels | date = May 15, 2018 | accessdate = May 15, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref> The game's Collector Edition, which includes a severed mutant head voiced by [[Andrew W.K.]], is set to be released alongside the standard edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/10/17447490/rage-2-collectors-edition-set-release-date|title=Rage 2 collector's edition is no less than creepy|first=Allegra|last=Frank|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=June 10, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> Players who preordered the game will have access to an exclusive mission and additional gameplay items.<ref name=\"preorder\"/> Willits revealed that the game will be a [[games as a service|game as a service]], and he promised that [[lootbox]]es would not be present in the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/05/17/rage-2-no-loot-boxes-but-live-service/|title=Rage 2 is a game as a service, but don't expect loot boxes|first=Sherif|last=Saed|work=[[VG 247]]|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> ''Rage 2'' was released on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] with [[Denuvo]] digital rights management. However, the game was cracked within a day because the version on Bethesda's own store did not use Denuvo. Denuvo was subsequently removed from the Steam release.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|url=https://kotaku.com/rage-2-drops-denuvo-drm-in-record-time-1834854493|title=Rage 2 Drops Denuvo DRM In Record Time|date=May 17, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jarred|last=Walton|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rage-2-patch-removes-denuvo-but-performance-is-worse/|title=Rage 2 patch removes Denuvo, but performance is worse|magazine=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc|Future]]|date=May 17, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn expansion pack titled ''Rise of the Ghosts'' was released on 26 September 2019. It introduced cheats, new vehicles, a new story, and pilotable mechs to the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bethesda.net/en/article/3AwowQ5sWLVhcUhWWw3NtE/rage-2-rise-of-the-ghosts-now-available|title=Rage 2: Rise of the Ghosts Now Available|work=[[Bethesda Softworks]]}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 73/100<ref name=\"mc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/rage-2 |title=Rage 2 for PC Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref><br>(XONE) 72/100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/rage-2|title=Rage 2 for Xbox One Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref><br>(PS4) 67/100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/rage-2|title=Rage 2 for PlayStation 4 Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-rage-2-552045.phtml|title=Review: Rage 2|last=Carter|first=Chris|publisher=[[Destructoid]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> \n| GI = 7/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/review/rage-2/a-blunted-bloodbath|title=Rage 2 Review - A Blunted Bloodbath|last=Tack|first=Daniel|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/rage-2-review/|title=Rage 2 review|last=James|first=Ford|publisher=[[GamesRadar+]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rage-2-review-walker-wasteland-ranger/1900-6417138/|title=Rage 2 Review|last=Higham|first=Michael|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2019/05/13/rage-2-review|title=Rage 2 Review|last=Stapleton|first=Dan|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| JX = 17/20<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/test/1042349/rage-2-le-fast-fps-survolte-en-monde-ouvert-tant-attendu.htm|title=Test du jeu Rage 2|author=Silent_Jay|publisher=[[Jeuxvideo]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| USG = 4/5<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/rage-2-review|title=Rage 2 Review|last=Williams|first=Mike|publisher=[[Jeuxvideo]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\nOn release, ''Rage 2'' received \"mixed or average reviews\" according to the [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].\n\nDaniel Tack from ''[[Game Informer]]'' rated the game a 7/10, praising the game's shooting mechanics and music but criticized the visuals, open-world and characters.<ref name=\"GI Rage2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/review/rage-2/a-blunted-bloodbath|title=Rage 2 Review - A Blunted Bloodbath - Game Informer |first=Daniel|last=Tack|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Dan Stapleton from ''[[IGN]]'' gave a rating of 8/10, comparing the game to 2016's ''[[Doom (2016 video game)|Doom]]'', praising the game for its gunplay and the open-world gameplay as well as the abilities and the visual style, but felt bemused about the use of [[microtransaction]]s as it featured no co-op or multiplayer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://au.ign.com/articles/2019/05/13/rage-2-review|title=Rage 2 Review - IGN|first=Dan|last=Stapleton|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 15, 2019|url-status=live|archivedate=May 15, 2019}}</ref> Michael Higham from [[GameSpot]] gave the game a 6/10, praising the game's combat and abilities, but criticized the humor, short length, narrative, characters, gameplay and side activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rage-2-review-wasted-land/1900-6417138/|title=Rage 2 Review - Wasted Land - GameSpot|first=Michael|last=Higham|work=GameSpot|date=May 14, 2019|accessdate=May 17, 2019|url-status=live|archivedate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Sales===\n''Rage 2'' was the best-selling retail game in the United Kingdom in its week of release, beating ''[[Days Gone]]'', although its physical sales figures were only 25% of the original game's launch-week sales.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dring |first=Christopher |title=UK Charts: Rage 2 is No.1 but fails to match original |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-05-20-uk-charts-rage-2-is-no-1-but-fails-to-match-original |work=GamesIndustry.biz |date=May 20, 2019 |accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref> In Japan, the PlayStation 4 version ''Rage 2'' was also the best-selling retail game during its first week of release, selling 12,146 copies.<ref>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |date=June 12, 2019 |url=https://gematsu.com/2019/06/famitsu-sales-6-3-19-6-9-19 |title=Famitsu Sales: 6/3/19 \u2013 6/9/19 [Update] |publisher=Gematsu |accessdate=June 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://bethesda.net/en/game/rage2/ Official site]\n\n{{id Software}}\n{{Avalanche Studios}}\n\n[[Category:2019 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Avalanche Studios games]]\n[[Category:Bethesda Softworks games]]\n[[Category:First-person adventure games]]\n[[Category:First-person shooters]]\n[[Category:Id Software games]]\n[[Category:Near-Earth asteroids in fiction]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Post-apocalyptic video games]]\n[[Category:Vehicular combat games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Video games using Havok]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Stadia games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Rage 2\n| image = Rage 2 cover art.jpg\n| developer = [[Avalanche Studios]]{{efn|Additional development by [[id Software]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/08/11/rage-2-is-primarily-being-developed-by-avalanche-studios-id-working-with-them-on-a-creative-level|title=Rage 2 Is Primarily Being Developed by Avalanche Studios, Id Working with Them on a Creative Level|first=Tom|last=Marks|work=[[IGN]]|date=August 10, 2018|accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref>}}\n| publisher = [[Bethesda Softworks]]\n| director = Magnus Nedfors \n| producer = {{Unbulleted list|Erik Olsen|Anders Strid}}\n| writer = {{Unbulleted list|Odd Ahlgren|Loke Wallmo}}\n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = Jeremy Miller<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2018/12/14/rethinking-wastelands-how-avalanche-brought-color-and-insanity-to-rage-2|title=Rethinking Wastelands: How Avalanche Brought Color And Insanity To Rage 2|first=Ben|last=Reeves|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=December 14, 2018|accessdate=February 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| engine =\n| composer = {{Unbulleted list|Johan Nilsson|Andreas Kinger|Eirik R\u00f8land{{efn|Additional music by Jukka Rintam\u00e4ki.<ref>{{cite video game |title=Rage 2 |developer=[[Avalanche Studios]] |publisher=[[Bethesda Softworks]] |date=2019-05-14 |platform=Windows |version= |scene=Ending credits |level= |language= |quote= }}</ref>}}}}\n| series = \n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Google Stadia|Stadia]]}}\n| released = May 14, 2019\n| genre = [[First-person shooter]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Rage 2''''' is a [[first-person shooter]] [[video game]] developed by [[Avalanche Studios]] in conjunction with [[id Software]] and published by [[Bethesda Softworks]]. The game is the sequel to the 2011 game ''[[Rage (video game)|Rage]]''. The game was released for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] on May 14, 2019. It received mixed reviews from critics, with praise for its combat but criticism for its story, characters, and open world gameplay.\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Rage 2'' is a [[first-person shooter]]. Players assume control of a ranger named Walker, who is free to explore the game's [[apocalyptic fiction|apocalyptic]] [[open world]].  Players are given control over some of Walker's attributes, such as their gender, skills, or attire. Walker is able to wield various firearms and tools to fight against enemies, including returning weapons such as the wingstick. Players can develop Walker's skills with Nanotrite-based powers. Through a mode called Overdrive, Walker's guns do more damage, enemies drop more energy and they get healed constantly \u2014 providing players with an aggressive way to mow down enemies.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://gamegator.net/news/article/rage-2-post-post-apocalypse|title=Rage 2 - Welcome the Post-Post-Apocalypse!|website=GameGator|language=en|access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/05/15/rage-2-gameplay-reveal/|title='Rage 2' brings the frenetic action of 'Doom' to an open world|first=Jon|last=Fingas|work=[[Engadget]]|date=May 15, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> Nanotrites from the first game, which act as special powers and ability boosts, can be used to increase combat efficiency. The game features [[vehicular combat]], including trucks, buggies and gyrocopters, with the player being able to drive any vehicle in the game's world.<ref name=\"preorder\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2018-rage-2-what-we-know-and-want/1100-6459136/|title=E3 2018: Rage 2 -- What We Know And Want|first=Edmond|last=Trans|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=June 7, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nPlayers assume control of Walker, the last Ranger of Vineland, who must survive in a world inhabited by dangerous mutants and crazed bandits after it was hit by the asteroid [[99942 Apophis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rage-2-trailer-shows-off-cars-guns-special-powers-and-a-weird-post-apocalypse/|title=Rage 2 trailer shows off cars, guns, special powers, and a weird post-apocalypse|last=Chalk|first=Andy|date=June 13, 2018|work=[[PC Gamer]]|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> The majority of humankind died during this apocalyptic event. While new settlements and factions emerged, a group called the Authority declared themselves the new military power. The game's prologue begins in Walker's home, Vineland, a city founded by former Ark residents and their descendants. Vineland gets stormed by the Authority's rebuilt Abadon mutant armies, and Walker's adoptive Aunt Prowley is killed by General Cross. Prowley leaves a pre-recorded holotape asking Walker to carry out Project Dagger, a mission conceived to stop General Cross. Walker is inducted as the last Ranger, a group of Ark survivors whose nanotrite-powered suits give them enhanced combat abilities. They are asked by Prowley's recording to find the three other members of Project Dagger; Loosum Hagar, Marshall, and Dr. Kvasir. Prowley's biological daughter, Lily, provides Walker with the Phoenix, an indestructible vehicle to travel the Wasteland, and promises to rebuild Vineland in the Ranger's absence.\n\nMarshall is found in the town of Gunbarrel. Walker is asked to assist him in restoring power to Gunbarrel before Marshall and retrieving Gulo, a scout sent by Marshall from an hostile enemy clan named the Immortal Shrouded. The scout's last defiant act was to swallow the recorder with the bunker's location, which Walker recovers from her already-carved-out gut. They proceed to the bunker, wiping out both the Immortal Shrouded and the Authority patrol sent to dislodge them, and secures the data necessary to penetrate the Authority's security scans.\n\nLoosum Hagar is the mayor of Wellspring, a major travel hub in the Wasteland. When Walker arrives at her office, the Ranger is forced to fight off an assassination attempt against the mayor, who she suspects Wasteland tycoon Klegg Clayton of masterminding the attack. Klegg tries to kill Walker after admitting he was on a first name basis with General Cross. Fighting through Klegg's henchmen, Walker warns Loosum of the plot against Wellspring and uncovers a Xerxes MK III Authority Predator tank hidden in Klegg's catacombs beneath the town. The Ranger follows Klegg to an Authority bunker, to witness General Cross put down his unsuccessful lackey for failing to deliver Wellspring. Exploring deeper into the facility, Walker finds evidence that the Authority is building massive Abadon mutants piece by piece, calling them \"Titans\" and planning to unleash them on the rest of the Wasteland. Walker tears the fusion core out of a huge, half-build Titan, causing a chain reaction that destroys the facility and simultaneously securing a power source for the Xerxes III Predator tank that is necessary to complete Project Dagger.\n\nDr. Anton Kvasir is a master of genetic manipulation tasked to create a nanotrite virus that would disable General Cross' ability to clone himself indefinitely to prolong his life. The scientist invites Walker into his sanctum, where he says he is held back from finishing his project by insufficient computing power. Walker is asked to land Eco-Pod 15, the last of a series of satellites tasked with re-seeding the Earth with life in the event that the Apophis meteor rendered the planet barren after impact. After entering EDEN Space Center, Kvasir hacks the Vault mainframe to grant Walker the status of [[President of the United States|POTUS]] to ensure they can access every aspect of the EDEN Project. Successful in lowering Eco-Pod 15 back to Earth, Walker slaves its processor to Kvasir's mainframe before being forced to fight off an Authority strike force. Kvasir sends Walker on a mission to retrieve a DNA sample from General Cross. Raiding an Authority base for the sample, Walker frees captives from Vineland whose DNA was used in horrific cloning and mutant experiments. Walker decapitates General Cross after defeating him in battle, though a fresh clone of the General escapes. Back at Kvasir's lab, the doctor uses Cross' severed head to produce the nanotrite virus that was his part of Project Dagger.\n\nWith the three components, Walker initiates the final phase of Project Dagger by infiltrating the Authority HQ. Able to gain entry to the compound by impersonating General Cross, the Ranger is discovered by the real general. General Cross meets Walker while riding a gigantic Cyber Titan, and the two battle. Killing the Titan, Walker stabs Cross in the eye with the Nanotrite Virus, causing his DNA to be corrupted to prevent future clones from being created. However, unbeknownst to Walker due to Kvasir's manipulation, the Ranger's own nanotrites are also susceptible to the virus. Choking to death alongside the broken body of General Cross, Walker is saved by the intervention of Lily, who returns them to Hagar's Wellspring office for medical treatment. With Lily's gun to his head, Dr. Kvasir works frantically to save the Ranger. When he succeeds, the doctor begs for his life from the enraged Lily, who spares him. The game ends with Walker regaining consciousness and thanking Lily for her help, promising to continue helping the Wasteland as the Last Ranger.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/rage-2-rage-1-story-1202840312/|title=Bethesda Confirms 'Rage 2' Will Continue 'Rage 1's' Storyline|first=Vikki|last=Blake|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 12, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n''Rage 2'' is a joint development between [[id Software]] and [[Avalanche Studios]]. Avalanche was selected as the collaboration partner for the project as id Software was impressed by Avalanche's work on ''[[Just Cause 3]]'', especially its physics-based emergent gameplay. According to [[Tim Willits]], the team hoped that the sequel could deliver on the promise made by the first game, which was limited by technology during its time of release. Willits added that ''Rage 2'' was designed to be the player's \"power fantasy\", thus they ensured that they will not feel underpowered at the beginning of the game. The game features a colorful color palette so as to distinguish itself from other id Software's games.<ref name=\"Willits interview\"/> ''Rage 2'' utilizes Avalanche Studios' proprietary Apex [[game engine]] instead of [[id Tech]], which had been used for the predecessor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/105027/rage-2-uses-just-cause-series-engine-instead-of-idtech|title=Rage 2 Uses Just Cause Series' Engine Instead of idTech|first=Charles |last=Singletary|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> The Apex engine allowed the team to create detailed indoor environments as well as broad outdoor locations, also allowing players to transition between these worlds without any loading screens.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Willits interview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/06/12/rage-2-tim-willits/|title=We asked id Software studio director Tim Willits about their Avalanche partnership, open world fatigue and Rage 2 on Switch|first=James|last=Billcliffe|date=June 12, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018|work=[[VG 247]]}}</ref> The game engine uses the [[Vulkan (API)|Vulkan]] API exclusively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techpowerup.com/review/rage-2-benchmark-performance-test/|title=RAGE 2 Benchmark Test & Performance Analysis|author=W1zzard|date=May 13, 2019|website=TechPowerUp}}</ref>\n\nA sequel to ''[[Rage (video game)|Rage]]'' was hinted by Bethesda's Pete Hines, who believed that both ''Rage'' and ''[[The Evil Within]]'' had sold enough to warrant sequels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/08/09/bethesda-discusses-rage-and-the-evil-within-sequels|title=Bethesda Discusses Rage and The Evil Within Sequels|first=Matt|last=Porter|work=[[IGN]]|date=August 9, 2016|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> In mid-May 2018, rumors of the sequel were fueled when [[Walmart]] Canada's website updated its video game sections with several as-yet-unannounced titles, which included ''Rage 2''. Bethesda poked fun at Walmart over social media in the following days, but this turned into more direct hints of the sequel's existence.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-05-10-despite-all-their-rage-bethesda-tweet-puts-walmart-in-a-cage | title = Despite all their Rage, Bethesda tweet puts Walmart in a cage | first = Wesley | last = Yin-Poole | date = May 10, 2018 | accessdate = May 14, 2018 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> Bethesda formally revealed ''Rage 2'' on May 14, 2018 with a teaser trailer and a gameplay trailer the next day.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/5/14/17351926/rage-2-trailer-ps4-xbox-one-pc-bethesda | title = Rage 2 trailer hints at silly sequel, mixing Mad Max with Borderlands  | first = Chris | last = Plante | date = May 14, 2018 | accessdate = May 14, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref> The game was released on [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] on May 14, 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rage-2-being-developed-in-part-by-just-cause-studi/1100-6458925/ | title = Rage 2 Being Developed In Part By Just Cause Studio; Confirmed For PS4, Xbox One, PC | first = Chris | last=  Pereira | date = May 14, 2018 | accessdate = May 14, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url =  http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/05/15/rage-2-release-window-gameplay-details-announced | title = Rage 2: Release Window, Gameplay Details Announced | first=  Joe | last = Skrebels | date = May 15, 2018 | accessdate = May 15, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref> The game's Collector Edition, which includes a severed mutant head voiced by [[Andrew W.K.]], is set to be released alongside the standard edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/10/17447490/rage-2-collectors-edition-set-release-date|title=Rage 2 collector's edition is no less than creepy|first=Allegra|last=Frank|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=June 10, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> Players who preordered the game will have access to an exclusive mission and additional gameplay items.<ref name=\"preorder\"/> Willits revealed that the game will be a [[games as a service|game as a service]], and he promised that [[lootbox]]es would not be present in the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/05/17/rage-2-no-loot-boxes-but-live-service/|title=Rage 2 is a game as a service, but don't expect loot boxes|first=Sherif|last=Saed|work=[[VG 247]]|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> ''Rage 2'' was released on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] with [[Denuvo]] digital rights management. However, the game was cracked within a day because the version on Bethesda's own store did not use Denuvo. Denuvo was subsequently removed from the Steam release.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|url=https://kotaku.com/rage-2-drops-denuvo-drm-in-record-time-1834854493|title=Rage 2 Drops Denuvo DRM In Record Time|date=May 17, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jarred|last=Walton|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rage-2-patch-removes-denuvo-but-performance-is-worse/|title=Rage 2 patch removes Denuvo, but performance is worse|magazine=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc|Future]]|date=May 17, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn expansion pack titled ''Rise of the Ghosts'' was released on 26 September 2019. It introduced cheats, new vehicles, a new story, and pilotable mechs to the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bethesda.net/en/article/3AwowQ5sWLVhcUhWWw3NtE/rage-2-rise-of-the-ghosts-now-available|title=Rage 2: Rise of the Ghosts Now Available|work=[[Bethesda Softworks]]}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 73/100<ref name=\"mc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/rage-2 |title=Rage 2 for PC Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref><br>(XONE) 72/100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/rage-2|title=Rage 2 for Xbox One Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref><br>(PS4) 67/100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/rage-2|title=Rage 2 for PlayStation 4 Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-rage-2-552045.phtml|title=Review: Rage 2|last=Carter|first=Chris|publisher=[[Destructoid]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> \n| GI = 7/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/review/rage-2/a-blunted-bloodbath|title=Rage 2 Review - A Blunted Bloodbath|last=Tack|first=Daniel|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/rage-2-review/|title=Rage 2 review|last=James|first=Ford|publisher=[[GamesRadar+]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rage-2-review-walker-wasteland-ranger/1900-6417138/|title=Rage 2 Review|last=Higham|first=Michael|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2019/05/13/rage-2-review|title=Rage 2 Review|last=Stapleton|first=Dan|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| JX = 17/20<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/test/1042349/rage-2-le-fast-fps-survolte-en-monde-ouvert-tant-attendu.htm|title=Test du jeu Rage 2|author=Silent_Jay|publisher=[[Jeuxvideo]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| USG = 4/5<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/rage-2-review|title=Rage 2 Review|last=Williams|first=Mike|publisher=[[Jeuxvideo]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\nOn release, ''Rage 2'' received \"mixed or average reviews\" according to the [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].\n\nDaniel Tack from ''[[Game Informer]]'' rated the game a 7/10, praising the game's shooting mechanics and music but criticized the visuals, open-world and characters.<ref name=\"GI Rage2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/review/rage-2/a-blunted-bloodbath|title=Rage 2 Review - A Blunted Bloodbath - Game Informer |first=Daniel|last=Tack|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Dan Stapleton from ''[[IGN]]'' gave a rating of 8/10, comparing the game to 2016's ''[[Doom (2016 video game)|Doom]]'', praising the game for its gunplay and the open-world gameplay as well as the abilities and the visual style, but felt bemused about the use of [[microtransaction]]s as it featured no co-op or multiplayer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://au.ign.com/articles/2019/05/13/rage-2-review|title=Rage 2 Review - IGN|first=Dan|last=Stapleton|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 15, 2019|url-status=live|archivedate=May 15, 2019}}</ref> Michael Higham from [[GameSpot]] gave the game a 6/10, praising the game's combat and abilities, but criticized the humor, short length, narrative, characters, gameplay and side activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rage-2-review-wasted-land/1900-6417138/|title=Rage 2 Review - Wasted Land - GameSpot|first=Michael|last=Higham|work=GameSpot|date=May 14, 2019|accessdate=May 17, 2019|url-status=live|archivedate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Sales===\n''Rage 2'' was the best-selling retail game in the United Kingdom in its week of release, beating ''[[Days Gone]]'', although its physical sales figures were only 25% of the original game's launch-week sales.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dring |first=Christopher |title=UK Charts: Rage 2 is No.1 but fails to match original |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-05-20-uk-charts-rage-2-is-no-1-but-fails-to-match-original |work=GamesIndustry.biz |date=May 20, 2019 |accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref> In Japan, the PlayStation 4 version ''Rage 2'' was also the best-selling retail game during its first week of release, selling 12,146 copies.<ref>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |date=June 12, 2019 |url=https://gematsu.com/2019/06/famitsu-sales-6-3-19-6-9-19 |title=Famitsu Sales: 6/3/19 \u2013 6/9/19 [Update] |publisher=Gematsu |accessdate=June 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*